---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import AceArt from "../components/AceArt.astro";

const description =
  "ACE Engine: read-only analytics for GPU job right-sizing. Ingests Slurm accounting exports, scores per-job efficiency, applies a conservative safety overlay, and produces a structured report with traceable recommendations and explicit assumptions.";
---

<BaseLayout title="ACE Engine — Plain Theory Labs" description={description}>
  <section class="section prose">
    <h1>ACE Engine</h1>
    <p class="thesis">
      ACE is a read-only analytics engine for GPU job right-sizing. It ingests Slurm accounting
      exports, scores per-job efficiency against measured or estimated telemetry, applies a
      conservative safety overlay, and produces a structured report with traceable recommendations
      and explicit assumptions. It does not touch your scheduler, modify job parameters, or change
      queue configurations. It reads, scores, and reports. Policy decisions remain with the
      operator.
    </p>

    <p>
      The current phase is 2B0. Phase 2B1 will add windowed telemetry joins from DCGM and
      Prometheus, JobID normalization improvements, and per-window provenance scoring so every
      recommendation is traceable to a measurement rather than an assumption.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>What ACE produces</h2>

    <p>
      ACE produces a per-job efficiency score, a right-sizing recommendation with a confidence
      label, and an environmental impact estimate covering energy, carbon, and water with every
      coefficient disclosed and configurable. The output is a JSON payload and a zero-dependency
      single-file HTML report with interactive tables, inline SVG charts, and summary cards that
      any operator can open on any machine and hand to any stakeholder.
    </p>

    <p>
      The MIT Supercloud run found 35,745 jobs with average GPU utilization of 25.7%, median of
      16%, 41% of jobs running under one minute, and 33% showing near-zero GPU activity.
      Environmental impact numbers are coefficient-based estimates, not metered totals. If your
      site has measured PUE or grid carbon intensity data, the engine uses it.
    </p>

    <div class="visual-center" aria-hidden="true">
      <AceArt />
    </div>
    <p class="figure-caption muted">Signal to structure: noisy scheduler traces become scored, reviewable outputs.</p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Pipeline</h2>

    <p>
      ACE runs five deterministic stages. Ingest takes a Slurm <code>sacct</code> export or
      canonical CSV, runs JobID normalization, and joins telemetry where available. Score computes
      per-job utilization, applies the over-request heuristic, and assigns a weighted review
      score. The safety overlay blocks low-confidence downsizing recommendations — nothing gets
      recommended that cannot be defended. Impact estimation projects energy, carbon, water, and
      cost from physical coefficients, all user-configurable and disclosed in the output. Report
      generates the JSON payload and single-file HTML with no external dependencies.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Assumptions and limits</h2>

    <p>
      Environmental impact numbers are coefficient-based estimates, not metered totals. Default
      coefficients are documented and configurable. If your site has measured PUE or grid carbon
      intensity data, use it. Phase 2B0 has no live telemetry join — utilization is derived from
      sidecar files or proxy estimates where direct measurement is not available. Confidence
      labels reflect this.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Status</h2>

    <p>
      Phase 2B0 is complete with 118 tests passing. ACE has been validated on the MIT Supercloud
      HPCA22 dataset and the Google Borg CPU proxy dataset. Phase 2B1 is in active development.
    </p>

    <p class="inline-links">
      <a href="/contact">Discuss a pilot &rarr;</a>
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
